  "siteName": "The Ancient Gaming Noob",
  "favicon": "",
  "text": "I played a lot of LOTRO over the weekend.  It was that or finish our taxes, and who wants to do that?  So even as I wrapped up the last post about getting to the Twenty-First Hall, I went back and pressed forward towards the first hall and the light at the end of the tunnel.  Or mines.  Or whatever. Moria Zones I actually got through Moria quicker than I thought I would.  On the other hand, I did binge a bit over the week and into the weekend… if you want to avoid thinking about your taxes a classic fantasy MMORPG with 150 levels is a prime candidate to help.  But even at my pace I spent a good eight days in Khazad-dum, which is about double what the fellowship took if I recall right.  So I am not getting and closer to them… though I still have an epic quest to go help Aragorn and Boromir pack for the journey.  I am pretty sure if I go back to Rivendell it will tell me it is still Decemeber 24th or some such.  So they are both waiting to go and have already passed through Moria, and more quickly than I managed. However they didn’t have to deal with all of the red tape and bureaucracy of the Iron Garrison.  They are keen to move in and take over the place right away… the war and Sauron be damned… and my impression is that of a epic scale version of the film The Money Pit, without the whole love story.  The place is a crumbling mess and, for whatever reason, it is on you to check out the structure, pick up rubble, and deal with the pest infestation… that last being made up of orcs, wargs, and various creepy crawlies. Not happy to see me… as usual Though, with the orcs, I suppose they are more like the former tenants being evicted… former tenants who have been pulling the copper wiring out of the walls and who have set up a meth lab or something. Really, it was disgusting.  The pool in one hall clearly had not been monitored for chlorine levels as the lease required. I am not sure how to even describe this So I spent a good deal of time in the place dealing with that sort of thing. As it turns out, once you get to the Twenty-First Hall, there isn’t a lot left of the place.  I spent a stretch in the Flaming Deeps, passing through the Crossroads of Ash a few times as I collects lost bits and pieces, smashed some lizard eggs, a dealt with the usual orc issues. Coming to the Crossroads of Ash… which is all covered with ash… as one might expect I lingered there for a while, once again not being a completionist, but soaking up all the xp and locations I could without going too far out of my way.  Pretty quickly though you end up in Nud-Melek, home to the second and first halls, and the exit sign becomes visible pretty quickly. You do end up going to the broken bridge of Khazad-dum a few times.  The quest chain is clearly VERY INTERESTED in point out to you that SOMETHING HAPPENED there that might indeed be relevant to your interests. As it happened, on the first quest driven visit to the location I hit level 60. The snowy tree graphic of a significant level or something Svanr there would bring me back again from the other side, getting there being super easy, barely an inconvenience, there being a path around maybe 200 meters to the north.  I marked up a map on a previous visit which I will now recycle. Chasm – Deep, wide, but not so long So you go up to the top of that loop, do a few quests cleaning up dwarf trash and stray orc, hang out with Svanr a bit, then head for the First Hall and the exit. Even there, however, Svanr has to guide you, and you do several farewell instance quests, first to go outside to see the sky in an instanced version of the Dimrell Dale, then you have to go back inside again. Svanr has another quest Then you have to go BACK to the broken bridge at just to reinforce that SOMETHING HAPPENED there… and to re-use that Balrog model I showed you a couple of posts back. Are Gandalf and that Balrog old friends or something? You watch a bit of that and get an oddly worded message on your screen along the lines of “Did the fellowship come this way?  Or was that all the lingering effect of that orc blotter acid you had to clean up a couple zones back?” Then you talk to the goat to end the whole thing… a sign that it might have been the blotter acid I think… and then Svanr has a couple of items to mention, some introductions give you to the quest givers outside, and then you’re done.  So I went forth into Lothlorien… and it was freaking night time.  The day/night cycle reasserts itself after about a week of it having no meaning. Night again… There were a number of alerts and updates and I gained a new title and I had an email from Galadriel, so well known as a chatty gossip who reaches out to random strangers. It says “Sent from my iPhone” at the bottom But those were all things to come. As for Moria, it went faster than I expected and wasn’t as grim as my memory had shaped it.  I managed to visit at least all the major encampments.  The stable master map shows I made a clean sweep of the place. Stable Master map, post Moria I did end up blowing a few mithril coins in the place.  Epic and sprawling though it is, it can be a bit of a maze and I was fine tossing a coin to get to the next stable master without having to blunder my way through another section or to get back to a quest giver as the end of an evening and bed time loomed. Along the way I also ended up getting the Busy Bee achievement, which comes from doing 300 daily tasks.  I am a firm believer in doing the daily tasks. The busiest of bees Those deeds up the number of tasks you can do, so are a self-reinforcing cycle. I also managed to get to kindred status with the Iron Garrison Guards. Practically a guard myself now There are only two factions in Moria that I saw, the guards and the miners.  I am close to kindred with the miners.  A couple more days of daily tasks and I could clinch that. And now Lothlorien lays before me. To Lothlorien… the old map… which is better frankly Outside, the first thing Svanr’s buddies set me to doing was killing orcs.  Same as it ever was. I am still a ways from Mirkwood, but it is visible over the next hill, past Lothlorien.",
